<HEAD>Sears Denies Reported Plans for Adding to Height of World's Tallest
Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. denied reports Saturday
that it plans to add stories to the Sears Tower because another
Chicago skyscraper might overshadow the world's tallest building.
   The Wall Street Journal and the Chicago Sun-Times reported that
Sears is planning to outdo two Chicago developers who announced
plans in May to erect a taller skyscraper only a few blocks from the
Sears building.
   ``Not to be outdone,'' Friday's Journal said, ``Sears quietly
began drawing up contingency plans to add at least 16 floors to its
tower _ topping the proposed unstart by at least one floor.''
   ``Absolutely not,'' Sears spokesman Doug Fairweather said when
asked if the story was true.
   The Sun-Times reported Saturday that Sears is preparing plans for
an addition, but neither the Sun-Times nor the Journal quoted Sears
officials by name.
   The Sears tower is for sale, and the Journal said the company is
preparing the plans to placate potential buyers who might balk at
the thought of owning the world's second-tallest building.
   Construction would be done by the new owner, the Journal said.
   ``There are no plans, nor has there been any formal study for
such a plan. Not a nickel has been spent,'' Fairweather insisted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

