<HEAD>Zoning OK'd for World's Tallest Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago City Council on Friday unanimously
approved a zoning request to allow construction of a 125-story
building, which would be 15 stories higher than the world's tallest.
   The building, proposed by the Chicago real estate development
firm Miglin-Beitler Inc., would rise 1,950 feet, 496 feet taller
than the Sears Tower, currently the world's tallest building.
   The proposed Miglin-Beitler Tower would be in the city's west
Loop area downtown, near the 110-story Sears Tower.
   The council approved the zoning request 44-0, said Alderman
William Banks, chairman of the Committee on Zoning.
   Developer Paul Beitler said the tower's skinny design will cater
to the ``new market of the 1990s'' _ consulting firms, small
corporations and other small tenants who can't afford entire floors
in fatter office buildings.
</TEXT>
