<HEAD>Taj Mahal West or 125-Story Megabuilding? Trump's LA Plans Unclear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump's new Taj Majal casino in
Atlantic City, with its minarets and huge stone elephants, has left
many here wondering _ or worrying _ what the mega-developer plans
for an encore.
   But details concerning Trump's grand design for the site of the
historic Ambassador Hotel remain by and large the sultan's secret.
   Three months ago, the New York billionaire revealed he had
become a partner in a group that bought the boarded-up hotel with
the intention of razing it and building a new project. The
development at the 24-acre site on Wilshire Boulevard would be
Trump's first in the nation's second-largest city.
   He's hinted that he may try to put up the world's tallest
building, a tower of 125 stories or more, if plans for a similarly
outsized building are thwarted in New York City.
   Such talk has worried environmentalists _ Bob Hattoy of the
Sierra Club quipped that Trump was giving the city an ``edifice
complex'' _ but it remains just talk.
   ``We haven't formally announced anything in terms of how tall or
how wide,'' said Barbara Res, the Trump Organization vice president
who is shepherding the deal.
   Whatever its shape, the $1 billion project would give Los
Angeles something it lacks _ a landmark comparable to the Eiffel
Tower or Rockefeller Center, Res said in a recent telephone
interview.
   ``We anticipate having a major shopping area, a luxury hotel _ a
very large one with a very, very large banquet and ballroom
facility, maybe on the order of 50,000 square feet _ a lot of
office space and a housing element,'' she said.
   The Ambassador was home to the Cocoanut Grove nightclub where
the rich and famous in Southern California came to play, but is
perhaps best known as the place where Robert F. Kennedy was
assassinated in 1968. The hotel, its glamour now faded, finally
closed in January 1989.
   With no specifics to react to yet, not even an artist's concept,
the potential opponents of Trump's development are left with little
to say.
   ``There's nothing on the table,'' said Jay Rounds, executive
director of the Los Angeles Conservancy, a non-profit historic
preservation group. ``We don't deal in critiques of press
conferences.''
   A spokesman for Mayor Tom Bradley, reflecting the views of
several local politicians, said, ``We need to wait until we see
specifics of the project before we can discuss it in detail.''
   The scarcity of details on design or financing has prompted
speculation that Trump wanted the publicity only to gain leverage
against New York officials who have held up his plans for a
150-story tower on the Hudson River.
   ``Perhaps the fact that I go out to L.A. will change things in
New York,'' Trump told The New York Times in February. He denied
trying to play New York and Los Angeles off against each other, but
added his plans for the world's tallest building ``could go to
either place, and it will only go to one.''
   Could such a building be put up in an earthquake-prone area?
   ``There's no inherent reason why you can't build a building in
the range of 125 stories to be resistant to an earthquake,'' said
Wilford Iwan, a professor of earthquake engineering at the
California Institute of Technology.
   But Iwan added that really big structures ``tend to be quite
flexible,'' and the way such a building would sway in a quake or
strong wind could make people inside feel uncomfortable.
   Another concern is fire, especially since city fire officials
acknowledged that the 1988 inferno in the 62-story First Interstate
tower, then the state's tallest building, came perilously close to
exceeding the metropolitan area's firefighting resources.
   Among those who voice few doubts about Trump's intentions is
Jackie Goldberg, president of the city's Board of Education.
   The Los Angeles Unified School District, which is busing 4,000
Wilshire-area students at a cost of $6 million a year, wants to
take over the property as the site for a desparately needed new
high school. But the board has found itself stymied repeatedly by
the Trump organization, Goldberg said.
   ``We're involved with somebody here who is accustomed to getting
his own way, and has the funds and the lack of public scrutiny to
do it,'' Goldberg fumed.
   When school officials asked the state Allocation Board for $120
million to pay for the land, they discovered that lobbyists hired
by Trump already had persuaded members of the obscure state agency
to withhold the funds.
   The board instead ordered district officials to work out a
compromise with the billionaire developer, whose representatives
offered to find an alternate site for the school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

