<HL> REAL ESTATE:
Besides Penney, What Else Is
In Store for Dallas Market?
---
By Roger Lowenstein
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 08/05/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> PLT JCP
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL)
CONSTRUCTION, MATERIALS (CON) </IN>
<TEXT>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES INC.'S move to the Dallas area in 1979 helped touch off a local real-estate boom. 
Now, the planned relocation to Dallas next spring by J.C. Penney Co. has people in the area hoping for a repeat. 

   Two other big corporations, a retailer and an industrial concern, are looking hard at the city. 
So is the American Cancer Society, which needs a new headquarters site. 
And the Japanese are in town, far afield from their usual real-estate hunting grounds on the East and West coasts. 

   C. Itoh &amp; Co. of Tokyo recently acquired half of the Chateau Plaza office building. 
Several Japanese have acquired land in the city, and Dai-ichi Mutual Life Insurance Co., Japan's second-largest insurer, quietly agreed last month with Equitable Real Estate Investment Management Inc. to jointly provide a $450 million convertible mortgage to the Dallas Market Center. 

   But there's certainly no real-estate boom just around the corner for Dallas. 
No one expects the market to recover from its deep slump before 1989, and many say 1989 is too optimistic a timetable. 
The office-vacancy rate is a flabby 26%. 
The city has 35 million square feet of empty space, more than all the office space in downtown Los Angeles. 
And, as federal regulators continue to put pressure on thrifts with shaky portfolios, more depressed properties are likely to be dumped on the market. 

   DESPITE ALL THAT, some people say that Dallas may be one of the first Sun Belt cities to emerge from the current slump. 
Michael Richwine, vice president of institutional real-estate services for Coldwell Banker, says, "Dallas is in better shape than most of the cities in the Southwest." 

   Mr. Richwine and others note that the Dallas economy is more diversified than other cities in the region. 
While the Houston market crashed with oil, the Dallas office glut was caused by overbuilding. 
"We developed the mentality that real estate was a basic industry," says Bernard Weinstein, director of the Center for Enterprising at Southern Methodist University. 
Offices were built because money was there to finance them, rather than to meet demand. 

   But demand is catching up, at least with new construction. 
The Dallas economy is absorbing five million square feet a year, about what's now coming on the market, and building is on the decline. 
And unlike Houston, Dallas should have 30,000 or so newcomers moving into the city this year, aiding real-estate demand. 
"If you look at the fundamentals, it's clear that the space will be absorbed over the next three to five years," Mr. Weinstein says of the city's empty offices. 

   Some buildings are so poorly located that they may not last that long. 
"We have some buildings that may never lease; some tear-downs," says Jay Dee Allen, who oversees the Southwestern and Mountain states for Cushman &amp; Wakefield. 
But overall, he says, "the climate is better than for any of the cities" in his turf. 

   ---
   'The Tallest Building West of Chicago' 

   Maguire Thomas Partners is known for classy architecture and imaginative, people-oriented buildings. 
So it seemed a bit out of character when the Santa Monica, Calif., office developer announced the ground-breaking for "the tallest building west of Chicago" -- Library Tower in Los Angeles. 

   In fact, Robert F. Maguire III, the company's founder and co-managing partner, was as surprised as anyone by Library Tower. 
"It turns out to be the tallest building in the West, but we didn't know that," he says. 
"There is a building in Seattle that is 76 stories. 
We always figured that was the biggest." 

   Library Tower will be 73 stories of pale, pink marble. 
But I.M. Pei &amp; Partners, the architect, recently discovered that at 1,017 feet, it will be 75 feet taller than Seattle's Columbia Center. 

   "We were absolutely not interested in having the tallest building," Mr. Maguire says. 
"It's not our style." 

   But economics took over. 
For the $350 million building to be profitable, Maguire Thomas figured it would need 1.3 million rentable square feet. 
I.M. Pei came up with a slender, stepped-back design. 
"We made some efforts to reduce the height," Mr. Maguire says, "but when we did that, it got squatty. 
It wrecked the form." 

   THE BUILDING is part of a plan to save the downtown Los Angeles library, which faces the project site and is one of the few noteworthy historic buildings in the city. 
Built in 1926, the library has been damaged by fires and neglected. 

   In return for the air rights to Library Tower and another building, Maguire Thomas has agreed to $125 million in cash and inkind improvements to rehabilitate and expand the library and to spruce up the nearby area. 

   The tower project, seven years in planning, was on hold while the developer looked for tenants. 
But recently, Arthur Andersen & Co.; Latham &amp; Watkins, a Los Angeles law firm, and Pacific Lighting Corp. signed on for half the space. 
Pacific Lighting also will be a 50-50 partner with Maguire Thomas in the venture. 

   One local mortgage banker says the developer "gave away the store to get those tenants." 
Mr. Maguire concedes that they did get attractive deals, but he says the rest of the building -- due to open in late 1989 -- should lease at above-market rents. 
Robert Ortiz, an official of Cushman Realty Co., agrees. 
"Every tenant we represent wants to look at Library Tower," he says. 

</TEXT>
