<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS: Architecture: Helmut Jahn Takes On the Big Apple </HL>
<AUTHOR> Ellen Posner </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> New York  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This spring, as the last panels of reflective glass and the last wafers of stone are installed on five enormous, weirdly shaped skyscrapers on five sensitive strategic Manhattan sites, Helmut Jahn will have put his mark on this city, much as he already has on the city of Chicago. 

   Located, respectively, next to City Center; across the street from the Chrysler Building; on 59th Street and Lexington Avenue; on 55th Street between Park and Madison avenues; and on 85th Street and Second Avenue (the America), these buildings add up to a hefty string of commissions for the 48-year-old German-born, Chicago-based architect, whose chronological peers, if they have any opportunity to work here at all, often are still settling for additions and renovations. 

   The bigger projects have been easier to come by in recent years, though, if an architect could demonstrate willingness (in this case, eagerness) to provide the maximum superficial splash for the fewest possible dollars, thereby endearing himself to real estate developers who are looking for an edge in a competitive market. 

   And Mr. Jahn's position is as follows: "Everyone today wants a signature building and you have to give the client what he wants. 
Sooner or later he reminds you that he is paying for it." (In other professions, of course, this abnegation of responsibility and expertise might be looked at askance.) 
Mr. Jahn does acknowledge that a city of nothing but "visible pretentious 'foreground' buildings" would be preposterous and "untenable." 
But he clearly believes that those other buildings, the ones that sit gracefully in their environments and that contribute to the fabric of the city, should be designed by someone else. 

   The curvy, cloudlike forms ("a subconscious preference") that Mr. Jahn employs; his slightly off-register palette of pastels, sometimes mixed with black; the combinations of disparate shapes that are given sudden torques, slants and chamfers; and the blown-up proportions that dwarf human beings, are surprising coming from a man who studied in Munich at a time when, as he tells it, the refined, minimalist, but materially rich aesthetic of Mies van der Rohe was "the gospel." 
And Mr. Jahn was a believer. 

   In fact he first came to the U.S. in the late '60s to attend Illinois Institute of Technology, which Mies had designed, where his reign had been absolute, and where his disciples continued to spread the word. 
Mr. Jahn's early work also was not unaffected by Miesian principles. 

   It wasn't very long, however, before the young architect began evolving his own "look" -- one which was not entirely out of keeping with the emerging cynicism and greed of the times: It involved effect for the sake of effect, the glorification of surfaces and exaggeration of technology. 
And eventually Mr. Jahn's unofficial emblem became the tall building wrapped in a taut, shimmery cellophanelike skin. 

   With its large stock of sober, muscular buildings, Chicago has been able to absorb Mr. Jahn's work; there, Xerox Centre's sweeping curve of white metal and reflective glass, or One South Wacker's long grids of pale pink and pale blue glass can seem like light relief. (For similar reasons, his recent Chryslerlike blue-glass tower can be accommodated in downtown Philadelphia). 
New York, on the other hand, already has plenty of fantasy and excess. 
And buildings such as Mr. Jahn's pink-granite-striped Park Avenue Tower on East 55th Street, which rises massively from the ground and sends arms of its facade out to wrap themselves against the sides of adjacent buildings and to claim the street from pedestrians, or the Lexington Avenue and 43rd Street building that splays and becomes wider at its top (described by the architect, with a straight face, as a gesture to the beautiful neighboring Chrysler Building) just seem antiurban and even scary. 

   And there are some other reasons for concern about Mr. Jahn's work. 
His first attributed building was a sports arena in Kansas City, Mo., the roof of which collapsed. 
A year after his wild, dizzying, circular State of Illinois Building opened in Chicago in 1985, the State of Illinois announced that it was initiating a lawsuit against Mr. Jahn's firm and its joint venture partners: It seems that the structure turned out to be difficult to heat in winter and nearly uninhabitably hot in summer. 
The magazine Progressive Architecture reported recently that Mr. Jahn's glassy, vaulted new terminal at O'Hare Airport had some glare problems inside and out -- the latter affecting the work of the facility's air traffic controllers. 
So when Mr. Jahn brags that he successfully fought against Chicago's fire codes so he could build his design of exposed steel supports, one starts to think about changing planes somewhere else. 

   Worse, the forces behind Helmut Jahn's endeavors in this city tend to be powerful. 
One can only guess, for example, why the Landmarks Preservation Commission, which has been known to drive small property owners crazy over a doorknob and that has been holding the line against Michael Graves's (problematic but at least thoughtful) extension to the Whitney Museum, simply rolled over for Mr. Jahn's ungainly CitySpire tower -- which was destined for a site adjacent to the landmark City Center -- and granted that design its never more hilariously named Certificate of Appropriateness. 

   It is interesting to speculate, too, about the acquiescence of the City Planning Department. 
There was, what one staff member describes as an "excruciating" process of determining "to a matter of inches" just how tall CitySpire could be (the calculations were based upon zoning regulations as well as upon allowances made in exchange for the developer's purchase of City Center's air rights and his promise to rehabilitate the theater within the landmark structure). 
And there was a formal ruling by the City Planning Commission. 
Afterward, however, someone on the architect's side discovered that thicker floor slabs were going to be necessary. 

   Thicker slabs, of course, meant a taller building -- that is, unless a floor was eliminated or some floor-to-ceiling height sacrificed. 
The building was built taller; the Landmarks Preservation Commission applied to the City Planning Commission on behalf of the developer for retroactive approval. 
The application was refused. 

   There was lots of outrage about the violation and talk about penalties, law enforcement and having the top 11 or 12 feet of CitySpire torn down. 
But in the face of a lawsuit brought by the developer against the city, the City Planning Department and the city's corporation counsel suddenly determined that a deal could be struck, which would make retroactive approval possible. 

   CitySpire now rises blank, wide and broad-shouldered to what will be its puny dome (according to the architect, this form has something to do with the powerful dome atop City Center). 
Hawked on television by none other than Robin Leach, with print ads that promise deliveries from the swank restaurant La Caravelle, the building, nevertheless, sports (what certainly looks like) grudging pennywise ornament and shoddy finishes. 
Its cramped apartments and airless interior spaces are the kind that give living in New York a bad name. 

   Mr. Jahn is now at work on, among other things, the "tallest building in Europe," which will be built in Frankfurt. 
But the moment of the meretricious design may be ending in New York. 

   Skidmore, Owings &amp; Merrill's new brand of sedate post-modernism, for example, is growing in popularity as a safe choice for bruised real estate developers. 
And some of the more egregious projects -- including Mr. Jahn's "world's tallest building" for Television City -- have been dying quiet deaths. 

   It may not be too late for something to be done about CitySpire. 
Because of the city's back flip, the building will be swept back into the approval process. 
A Certificate of Appropriateness or even a Certificate of Occupancy could be denied -- either of which would set a precedent. 

</TEXT>
