<HEAD>Sale of Sears Tower Still Up in the Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has plenty of time to sell
its towering headquarters building, analysts say _ if it sells it at
all.
   A no-sale option reportedly is under consideration by the
nation's largest retailer since its prospective sale of Sears Tower
to a Canadian developer got sidetracked last week.
   Sears declined to comment Monday on the report in this week's
Crain's Chicago Business, which did not identify its sources for the
story.
   One option being considered, according to Crain's, was a
refinancing plan that would amount to a new mortgage on the property.
   Among Sears watchers, the item was received as one more rumor
swirling in the wind around the world's tallest building.
   ``I'm convinced the tower is to be sold,'' said Walter Loeb, a
retail analyst who follows Sears for Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New
York. But, he added, ``I think it may be sitting on the shelf a
while longer.''
   Retailing analysts said Sears' investment value would not suffer
if the tower were not sold by year's end, as the company had planned.
   But Sears had planned to use proceeds from the sale to pay off
the money it borrowed for its stock repurchase program.
   And reducing its debt, reported by Sears as $2 billion in a July
31 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, remains a
powerful incentive for Sears to sell its tower, Loeb said.
   Some observers believe Sears could still end up selling the
110-story, 1,707-foot landmark to Olympia &amp; York Developments Inc.,
the Toronto-based company that, until last week, appeared ready to
buy Sears Tower for a widely reported $1.04 billion.
   The prospective sale got stalled in a dispute over which party
should shoulder a steep increase in property taxes likely to result
from a post-sale reassessment.
   Olympia &amp; York declined to comment on the tower sale, or on
whether the firm was backing out in order to devote more resources
to bankrolling the cash-starved Canadian retailer Campeau Corp.
   Olympia &amp; York conditionally agreed Friday to loan Campeau $250
million in a deal that was expected to give the Toronto developer
greater influence over Campeau's management and a greater ownership
stake.
   Sears announced last October it would sell the tower as part of a
restructuring plan that included an everyday low-price retailing
policy, the transfer of its retailing division headquarters from the
tower to suburban Hoffman Estates in the early 1990s, and a buyback
of 40 million shares, or about 10 percent, of its outstanding stock.
   Olympia &amp; York emerged as the leading bidder in July but the
negotiations were rocky. Sears apparently insisted its name remain
on the building after the sale and the Canadians reportedly had
trouble finding a large tenant to anchor the 2 million square feet
of office space Sears is vacating in the 15-year-old building.
   British-based publisher Maxwell Communications Corp. was said to
have been interested in consolidating its Chicago operations in
Sears Tower but is now considering other quarters, including a
125-story skyscraper proposed by local developers Miglin-Beitler
Developments Inc. that would be taller than the Sears Tower.
   ``We submitted a bid (to Maxwell) on Friday,'' said
Miglin-Beitler spokesman Mark Jarasek.
