<HL> Sale Price of Sears Tower Is Expected To Break U.S. Office Building Record </HL>
<AUTHOR> Roger Lowenstein (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> S </CO>
<IN> REL TNM </IN>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. should be able to sell its Sears Tower headquarters for $800 million to $1.2 billion and break the record for the sale of a U.S. office building, real estate analysts say. 

   As the world's tallest building and Chicago's best-known landmark, analysts say it should attract a flood of interest from Japanese and other foreigners, as well as from capital-rich, opportunity-scarce U.S. pension funds. 

   "You're talking about one of the prime trophy buildings not only in Chicago but in the country," says Robert Rosen, president of Frain Camins &amp; Swartchild, Inc., a big Chicago real estate broker. 
"You have the kind of property that will attract the biggest pension money in the world, and with very aggressive buyers." 

   However, Sears plans to move out all but 600 of its 8,700 employees in the tower, meaning that roughly two-thirds of the building could become vacant. 
Chicago could thus suffer one of the greatest corporate defections of any city in years. 

   The market value of the building could vary widely depending on how fast the employees are moved out and on whether Sears assumes some of the risk for leasing the space. 

   "It becomes very speculative," says Willard Brown, chairman of Rubloff Inc., a Chicago real estate concern. 
If too much space is dumped on the market at once, he says, "it could have a major depressing effect" on the value of the building. 

   Sears says it will move the employees, who are part of the Sears merchandise group, over a two-year period which will begin after it has chosen a new location. 
The retailer will keep its corporate staff and headquarters in the Sears Tower. 

   The company said the merchandise employees will be moved to a less expensive site, possibly outside of Chicago. 
"We don't want to use space that could bring a premium if isn't necessary," a Sears spokesman said. 
"These are operations that can be done in lower cost real estate." 

   The dark gray, glass and steel Sears Tower stands 110 stories and 1454 feet (1,707 feet including the twin antenna towers atop it). 
The building, which opened in 1973, attracts 1.5 million paying visitors annually -- more people than paid to see the Chicago White Sox play this year. 

   The tower, on South Wacker drive, has 3.6 million rentable square feet, 98% of which is occupied. 
Brokers say the best commercial buildings in Chicago fetch $250 to $300 a square foot, putting the Sears building in the $1 billion range. 

   The value of the tower will be lessened because of the relocation of the Sears employees. 
New tenants in Chicago usually demand a period of free rent and significant physical improvements, costs which Sears will probably have to absorb. 

   But brokers say the intangible value of owning a landmark could compensate for that. 
Mr. Rosen says "trophy buildings are difficult to value because you have to ask what motivates people." 

   Adds Mr. Brown: "Without any question, someone is going to overpay for the ego of owning the world's tallest building." 

   Sears, which retained Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. to handle the sale, could fetch a higher price by contracting to lease back space from the buyer at a high rent. 

   Previous records for U.S. office buildings include Citicorp's sale of parts of two Manhattan buildings for $670 million and BankAmerica Corp.'s sale of its San Francisco headquarters for $660 million. 

   The vacancy rate for Chicago's prime buildings is 11%, and the city's real-estate market is generally considered healthy. 
However, Homart Development Co., a real estate development subsidiary of Sears, is planning to build a two-million square foot building across the street from the Sears Tower. 
If Homart breaks ground next spring, as scheduled, it would be in competition with Sears Tower and would potentially reduce its value. 

   Sears said it would retain the Homart subsidiary, one of its most valuable real estate assets. 
Homart owns 21 shopping centers and 19 office buildings. 
Shopping centers currently are a hot item and are selling for as much as 20 times cash flow. 

   However, Sears said it would sell its Coldwell Banker Commercial Group subsidiary, the country's largest commercial broker. 

   Coldwell Banker Commercial is expected to sell for $150 million to $225 million, real estate industry sources said. 
It will earn an estimated pretax profit of $25 million to $30 million this year on revenue of roughly $400 million. 
Sources close to the Los Angeles-based broker said Coldwell's managers might buy the business from Sears in a leveraged buy-out. 
James Didion, chairman of the group, declined to comment. 

   In line with Sears's decision to remain strong in consumer businesses, the company will hang on to its huge Coldwell residential housing brokerage business. 

</TEXT>
