<HEAD>Auctioneer Proposes Public Auction for Sears Tower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who wants to buy the Sears Tower?
   Not me, says Donald Trump.
   Not us, say the Japanese.
   But local real-estate auctioneer Joel Zegart believes these big
spenders will be among the bidders if Sears, Roebuck and Co. buys
his proposal to hold a public auction for the world's tallest
building.
   ``I think it's a smokescreen,'' Zegart, president of JBS &amp;
Associates Inc., said Wednesday of the many denials among those seen
as the most likely bidders for the 110-story headquarters of the
nation's largest retailer.
   ``I think a lot of people are interested and they just aren't
showing their cards yet,'' he said.
   Sears announced Monday it would sell its famed skyscraper as part
of a corporate restructuring designed to boost profits.
   Sears spokesman Douglas Fairweather said the company received a
number of inquiries following its announcement, but he would not
reveal the identities of the interested parties.
   Fairweather also would not comment on the idea of a public
auction.
   He said the sale, which is being handled by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
in conjunction with Sears' own Coldwell Banker real-estate and Dean
Witter Reynolds financial units, would be negotiated privately with
selected prospective buyers who would be invited to submit bids.
   But Zegart, whose firm specializes in auctions of large
investment properties, said a public auction open to all would
generate tremendous interest and result in a sale at the highest
price Sears could hope to receive.
   He said he would start the bidding at $800 million. Analysts say
the building could fetch as much as $1.8 billion.
   Zegart, comparing the one-of-a-kind Sears Tower to a work of art,
said an auction of the building could be as lucrative as the 1987
auction of Van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' was to the seller in that case.
   Japan's Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance Co. paid $40 million for
the painting by the Dutch Impressionist.
   ``The Sears Tower is a building that you'll never see reproduced
again,'' Zegart said.
   ``You're buying a piece of Chicago when you buy the Sears Tower.
It's the gem of the downtown. It's history, it's a landmark, it's
known around the world.''
   Several Japanese firms say those are precisely the qualities that
make them wary.
   ``This is like buying a piece of America's heart,'' Tokyo-based
investment analyst Masahiko Muranaka told the Chicago Tribune.
   ``That building is a symbol of America and no Japanese company
would be courageous enough to try and buy it,'' Naoya Nishimura,
manager of overseas real estate for Mitsubishi Trust &amp; Banking Co.,
told the Tribune. ``It would be like trying to buy the Empire State
Building.''
   The Trump Organization, which was also seen as a likely bidder
for the tower, is not interested in the Sears building, spokeswoman
Norma Foerderer said.
   Donald Trump, who made his name and fortune in New York real
estate, owns Manhattan's Plaza Hotel and Trump Tower, as well as
other properties there and in Atlantic City, N.J. He recently agreed
to buy Eastern Airlines' northeastern shuttle service.
   Sears, struggling to improve its earnings after three consecutive
quarters of declining profits, announced the planned sale of the
tower as part of a restructuring that also included the proposed
sale of its Coldwell Bankers commercial real estate subsidiary.
Sears also said it would buy back 10 percent of its 380 million
outstanding shares and take $425 million in fourth-quarter charges.
   The company said it would concentrate on consumer-oriented
businesses _ retailing, insurance, residential real estate and
financial services. It announced a revamping of its retailing
strategy, saying it would adopt the everyday low pricing policy that
has worked for its discount store competitors.
</TEXT>
