<HEAD>Atrium Pioneer's Reputation Takes a Blow in Debt Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financing difficulties brought on by debt have
delivered a blow to John C. Portman's reputation, but the Atlanta
architect-developer's lieutenants say obituaries are premature.
   Despite the recent series of emergency meetings with creditors
over Portman's unsecured loans, officials of The Portman Cos.
maintain their operation is strong and its ventures are moving full
steam ahead.
   ``We've been in business 30 years and will be in business 30
more. The financing on our major projects is firmly in place. There
is no threat to the concrete and steel buildings of the Portman
Companies,'' executive vice president Sam Williams said Wednesday,
following the latest session with creditors.
   Williams said the focus of the meetings is to create a pool of
collateral to back the company's unsecured loans - those that are
not supported by assets or other collateral. He said he expected an
agreement to be reached within two weeks.
   Williams said Portman has no intention of backing out of any of
his current projects, though some, notably a 60-story office tower
in downtown Atlanta, are going up under less than ideal
circumstances.
   The Atlanta venture, to be called One Peachtree Center and
designed as the tallest skyscraper in the South, has been launched
amid a period of rising vacancy rates in the city's office
buildings.
   Williams argued that the severity of the downtown office vacancy
situation has been inflated because most calculations have factored
in two other skyscraper projects that have since been abandoned.
   Another major Atlanta office building, 191 Peachtree Tower, is
under construction now and nearing completion. Williams contends
that the Portman project, currently in its early stages of
construction, will be in a prime position as the newest kid on the
block when it opens in 1991.
   ``In essence, we now have the market position of the only new
office tower in downtown Atlanta with space available,'' Williams
said. ``Real estate, like any other business, goes in cycles. ...
Who's to say what cycle we will be in in the third quarter of 1995?
Our crystal ball is not that good but we've been through real
estate storms before.''
   Portman, who declined to be interviewed for this article, has
been on the defensive before, though rarely for his business
acumen.
   His architectural style, marked by streamlined exteriors and
expansive indoor atriums, have tended to be popular among the
masses but maligned by critics, who accused Portman of building
urban fortresses.
   Portman has steadfastly defended his modernist architecture as
``for people and not things.''
   After building his Peachtree Center cluster of office towers,
hotels and trade marts in downtown Atlanta, Portman went on to
major projects in cities including New York, San Francisco and
Singapore.
   As the real estate market began to slump over the last three
years, however, Portman borrowed heavily and refinanced existing
projects to launch new ventures.
   Among his new developments are the $300 million One Peachtree
Center; the $155 million Inforum technology mart, which opened last
year in Atlanta; the $90 million San Francisco Fashion Center,
which opened during the summer; and the $195 million Shanghai
Center, an office-hotel-retail complex opening next month in China.
   Portman's operation is private and does not release financial
data, though his current debt load has been reported to be more
than $1.6 billion.
   He has been sued recently by DG Bank Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank for allegedly failing to make a $3 million loan
repayment. And on Sept. 1 he stopped making payments to one of his
main creditors, Equitable Life Assurances Society of the United
States, on a $332.6 million mortgage for his flagship Peachtree
Center complex in Atlanta.
   Williams said the company's problems are only with unsecured
creditors, who hold about 5 percent of the company's loans. A
spokesman for Equitable this week declined to comment on the talks
with Portman, though two other creditors, CitiBank and Swiss Bank
Corp., said ``positive progress'' was made at the latest meeting.
   The 65-year-old Portman has made some bold architectural and
business decisions during his career, but publicly has maintained a
reticent image. He makes few public appearances, except to announce
new developments.
   Yet the talks with creditors have made him a reluctant front
page item over the last month. It is a position, say some who are
close to Portman, that the businessman doesn't like.
   Insurance executive Jesse Hill Jr., a friend of Portman, charged
that much of the media coverage has been based on speculation and
has weakened Portman's position in negotiating with the bankers.
   ``The man is obviously restructuring his finances,'' said Hill,
president of Atlanta Life Insurance Co. ``He's in negotiations and
if somehow the press wouldn't give him this terrible beating, he
has the assets and under normal circumstances he could work it
out.''
   Hill said he was especially offended by those who have grouped
Portman with New York developer Donald Trump and other high-flying
1980s entrepreneurs whose debt-financed empires have taken a dive
in the new decade.
   ``There is some constant effort to compare John Portman to
Donald Trump,'' Hill said. ``Trump is no John Portman, and Portman
is no Trump.
   ``Portman is a Horatio Alger story. He didn't have a Rockefeller
Center - he built one. The man is in a class by himself.''
   B. Eugene Griessman, a professor in the college of management at
Portman's alma mater, Georgia Tech, profiled the
architect-developer for a 1987 book on achievers. He said it is
Portman's nature to brush aside such obstacles when he has his mind
set on a project.
   ``He's a risk taker. His next project is always his favorite,''
said Griessman.
   Williams said Portman's current problems stem from tightened
banking regulations that have followed the real estate slump and
the savings and loan crisis. Banks are requiring lenders to come up
with stronger backing for loans, he said.
   ``Almost every real estate company in America will have to deal
with it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

