<HEAD>Sears Refinancing Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to include total value of refinancing deal; picks
up 3rd graf, `AEW Partners ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. today announced it has
reached agreement with a Boston property investment firm to
refinance the Sears Tower, the world's tallest building and the
retailer's corporate headquarters.
   The $850 million refinancing deal delays a sale of the 110-story
skyscraper in downtown Chicago for at least 15 years.
   AEW Partners, a limited partnership managed by Aldrich, Eastman
&amp; Waltch Inc., will finance a 15-year mortgage on the tower and
related properties and have an option to buy the building, Sears
said in a news release.
   The deal will produce net proceeds of $815 million for Sears,
the nation's largest retailer, which had contemplated selling the
Chicago landmark. Sears said it expects to close the deal by the
middle of next summer.
   The company said that ``as a result of lower interest rates and
the positive long-term prospects for the commercial real-estate
market, this financing transaction offers more net cash and
attractive features than alternative structures.''
   Just over a year ago, Sears announced its intention to sell the
15-year-old tower as part of a corporate restructuring designed to
halt a slide in its profitability.
   The restructuring, which brought major changes in the retailer's
merchandising and pricing policies, also included moving Sears'
retail division headquarters from the tower to an office complex
that will be built in suburban Hoffman Estates.
   Sears began exploring the refinancing option in September after
a prospective sale of the 1,707-foot building to Canadian developer
Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. collapsed. The two reportedly
couldn't agree on which party would pay the increased property
taxes certain to result from a reassessment of the property after a
sale.
   The failed deal with Olympia &amp; York was reportedly for $1
billion. When Sears first announced plans to sell the building,
real-estate experts had speculated it would fetch $1.2 billion to
$2 billion.
</TEXT>
